<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - world]]></title><link/> https://www.wsj.com/news/world <atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/wsj/en-us/world" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - world - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 7 月 22 日星期六 14:32:58 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[As Heat Waves Spread, So Too Do Unruly Climate Protests]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>活动人士正在采取激进措施让政府减少排放，但担心会疏远他们希望赢得的一些人<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820700/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="在英国谢菲尔德举行的世界斯诺克锦标赛期间，一名“停止石油”抗议者投掷橙色粉末。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>在英国谢菲尔德举行的世界斯诺克锦标赛期间，一名“停止石油”抗议者投掷橙色粉末。迈克·埃格顿/祖玛出版社<span>迈克·埃格顿/祖玛出版社</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001069741"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001069741"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/james-hookway" itemprop="url" rel="author">詹姆斯·胡克威</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 22 日上午 5:52（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/as-heat-waves-spread-so-too-do-unruly-climate-protests-a896cb1"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>本月早些时候，几名气候抗议者在夜色掩护下来到西班牙南部的高尔夫球场，拍摄了自己将水泥倒入洞中的镜头。</p><p>他们总共瞄准了 10 个高尔夫球场，这些高尔夫球场在干旱气候下是出了名<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/golf-courses-stay-green-use-less-water-8b6f3435?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">的耗水大户</a>。一些抗议者种植了鲜花和蔬菜。其他人则展开标语，上面写着“为了气候正义，高尔夫球场关闭”或“水是共同利益”。</p><p>经过多年的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/cop26-protesters-in-glasgow-push-for-action-from-leaders-11636208381?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">请愿和集会</a>，越来越多的气候活动人士开始采取直接行动，有时他们会无视法律或引发安全担忧，因为他们传达的信息是，随着今年夏天<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/extreme-heat-waves-across-the-world-photos-7cc1544d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">气温攀升</a>至历史新高，政府需要采取更多措施来减少排放。许多人面临牢狱之灾。</p><p>在英格兰，他们跳到球场或桌子上投掷橙色纸屑或粉末，扰乱了比赛，扰乱了温布尔登和斯诺克世界锦标赛等体育赛事。两名妇女将亨氏番茄汤<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/protesters-throw-soup-on-van-goghs-sunflowers-painting-in-london-gallery-11665757510?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">罐头扔到</a>伦敦国家美术馆文森特·梵高的《向日葵》上。 （ <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/museum-food-throwing-protesters-11667829440?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">它被一层玻璃保护</a>。） 在周五的英国公开赛上，美国高尔夫球手比利·霍舍尔在皇家利物浦球场第<sup>17</sup>洞帮助驱散了一名抗议者。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820721?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">灭绝叛乱组织发布的一张照片显示，抗议者瞄准的几个西班牙高尔夫球场之一的果岭上挖出了植物。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：讲义/法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>今年早些时候，格蕾塔·通伯格因<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/greta-thunberg-detained-by-police-in-germany-during-coal-mine-protest-11673981053?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">抗议德国一座煤矿而</a>被拘留，而美国的气候活动人士则关闭了加拿大天然气管道的阀门，并爬上新英格兰<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/coal-makes-a-comeback-as-the-world-thirsts-for-energy-11656936180?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">燃煤电厂</a>的烟囱将其关闭。</p><p>本周，迪士尼财富继承人阿比盖尔·迪士尼与其他几名活动人士因封锁私人飞机使用的机场而在汉普顿被捕。她在推特上写道：“这个星球最不需要的就是亿万富翁排放温室气体才能到达他们富丽堂皇的海滨别墅。”</p><p>其中比较不寻常的组织之一是轮胎灭火组织，他们的使命是偷偷接近欧洲各地的耗油量大的SUV，放出轮胎中的空气，以阻止人们购买它们。超过 10,000 辆车辆因此被禁用，至少是暂时的。</p><p>这些自卫策略在环保人士中引发了一场争论，争论的焦点是此类抗议活动是否会激怒他们需要拉拢的人，从而弊大于利——学者们将这种情况称为活动家的困境。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="465" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820725?width=700&amp;height=465" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">格蕾塔·通伯格 (Greta Thunberg) 因德国煤矿扩建抗议活动而被警察带走。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Federico Gambarini/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>瑞典大学教授安德烈亚斯·马尔姆（Andreas Malm）的著作《如何炸毁管道》最近被改编成电影，他在 2007 年首次与其他活动人士一起开始对 SUV 轮胎进行放气。他认为，这一趋势显然是朝着更大胆、更激烈的特技方向发展，目的是让人们摆脱自满情绪，而且在许多情况下，破坏行为是合理的。</p><p> “年轻的气候活动人士有一种感觉，我们迄今为止所做的还不够，”他在斯德哥尔摩通过电话表示。</p><p>然而，有一条微妙的界限要走。马尔姆说，封锁道路和其他不分青红皂白的行为激怒了那些只需要上班或回家的人。</p><p>两年前，活动人士封锁了环绕伦敦的 M25 高速公路，导致交通严重延误，英国 YouGov 进行的一项民意调查发现，59% 的受访者反对抗议活动。随着“Just Stop Oil”和“Tire Extinguishers”等团体以其突击队式的战术脱颖而出，“灭绝叛乱”等较大的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/climate-change-protests-disrupt-london-for-fourth-day-400-arrested-11555593678?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">运动团体大多将注意力从直接行动转向动员大规模</a>示威活动。</p><p>英国诺丁汉特伦特大学讲师希瑟·阿尔贝罗认为，历史表明，有时激进的运动可以帮助推进更为温和的抗议活动。相比之下，激进的妇女参政论者通过破坏财产，使妇女参政论者争取妇女投票权的运动显得不那么令人担忧。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820740?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">本周，随着热浪席卷南欧，雅典附近发生了一场野火。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>现在，任何活动都可能成为目标，从音乐会到电影首映式，再到外出打高尔夫球。</p><p>最近，戴夫·格里斯瓦尔德 (Dave Griswald) 在苏格兰布劳蒂费里 (Broughty Ferry) 海滨帮助他的朋友给一辆深蓝色奥迪 SUV 的轮胎重新充气，希望能在附近的高尔夫球场打球。</p><p> “这是他们第三次打我，”朋友说。</p><p>该地区是邓迪的富裕郊区，当地人担心所涉及的安全问题。镇议会议员克雷格·邓肯(Craig Duncan)表示，他承认活动人士抗议的权利，但提出了一个问题：如果有人在行驶到繁忙道路上时才意识到轮胎已经漏气，可能会发生什么情况。</p><p>在其他地方，耐心就更少了。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>您是否同意在气候变化抗议中越来越多地采用直接行动？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>伦敦的小报将“停止石油”抗议者描述为“生态暴徒”或流氓，他们封锁道路，作为他们让人们摆脱私人交通并鼓励他们转向公共交通运动的一部分。在一场英格兰与澳大利亚的比赛中，一名板球运动员将一名抗议者从球场上驱逐，被许多媒体称赞为英雄。</p><p>与此同时，法国民意调查公司 Odoxa 在本周《费加罗报》发表的一项调查中发现，73% 的受访者希望当局追踪并逮捕计划破坏敏感地点的活动人士。</p><p>就抗议者而言，他们越来越冒着入狱的风险来表达自己的观点。</p><p>今年 4 月，英国法院判处土木工程师摩根·特罗兰 (Morgan Trowland) 三年监禁，以及活动家马库斯·德克尔 (Marcus Decker) 两年零七个月监禁，罪名是爬上横跨泰晤士河的伊丽莎白二世女王大桥 200 英尺，展开“停止石油”横幅。</p><p>在宣判前，特罗兰表示，他和德克尔反对钻探任何新的石油或天然气井。 “我不会参与其中，”他说。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820747?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">本月早些时候，气候活动人士冲破了汉堡机场的围栏。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：乔纳斯·格林/祖玛出版社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>向梵高画作泼番茄汤的两人将于明年 7 月因刑事毁坏罪受审，两人均表示不认罪。</p><p>内政大臣苏埃拉·布雷弗曼 (Suella Braverman) 称，英国限制抗议活动的新法律是对抗她所谓的“吃豆腐的工薪阶层”的必要措施，这表明更多的抗议者可能最终入狱。</p><p>与此同时，在德国，自称“最后一代”的气候活动人士上周将自己粘在跑道上，封锁了汉堡和杜塞尔多夫机场的航班数小时，要求政府采取更多措施减少排放，包括终止对航空公司使用的燃料煤油的免税。</p><p>官员们非常愤怒。交通部长表示，抗议者正在进行犯罪行为，而司法部长马可·布施曼表示，他们阻止人们享受应有的假期，从而导致社会两极分化。</p><p>组织者表示，这正是重点。</p><p>写信给 James Hookway： <a href="mailto:James.Hookway@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">James.Hookway@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 22 Jul 2023 09:52:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/as-heat-waves-spread-so-too-do-unruly-climate-protests-a896cb1</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/as-heat-waves-spread-so-too-do-unruly-climate-protests-a896cb1<author><![CDATA[James Hookway]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>内乱</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>社会问题</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>内乱</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>社会问题</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Race to Avert an Oil Spill That Could Cost $20 Billion to Fix]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>打捞小组的目标是在 FSO Safer 号腐烂的船体分解之前，从其腐烂的船体中吸走超过 100 万桶石油<figure><img src="https://www.wsj.com/articles/[object" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>一个国际专家小组已开始努力在一艘废弃油轮上转移超过一百万桶石油，以免其从也门红海沿岸泄漏。 《华尔街日报》的苏尼·拉斯穆森 (Sune Rasmussen) 解释了这一高风险行动的利害关系。照片：Yahya Arhab/Zuma Press <span></span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001072850"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001072850"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sune-engel-rasmussen" itemprop="url" rel="author">Sune Engel Rasmussen</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name">Saleh al-Batati</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 22 日上午 5:30 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-race-to-avert-an-oil-spill-that-could-cost-20-billion-to-fix-85a884ea"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>多年来，也门<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/iran-agrees-to-stop-arming-houthis-in-yemen-as-part-of-pact-with-saudi-arabia-6413dbc1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">饱受内战蹂躏</a>，另一场灾难在该国红海沿岸隐约可见，一艘生锈的油轮面临着破裂的危险，超过一百万桶石油泄漏到脆弱的生态系统中。</p><p>自 2015 年以来，FSO Safer 号<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/decaying-yemen-oil-tanker-at-risk-of-spilling-into-red-sea-11601653685?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">一直在距也门海岸 5 英里处搁浅，</a>国际组织和专家们惊恐地看着它开始崩溃。如果它破裂或爆炸，泄漏的石油量可能是 1989 年阿拉斯加埃克森·瓦尔迪兹号灾难中泄漏的石油量的四倍，从而扰乱世界上最繁忙的航道之一，并关闭向这个饱受战争蹂躏的国家运送人道主义援助的港口。联合国估计，清理工作将花费超过 200 亿美元，而且永远无法完全完成。</p><p>本周末，联合国领导的国际专家小组计划开始一项大胆的行动，以吸走“安全号”上全部不稳定的货物。</p><p>这个计划充满了危险。它涉及将一艘非常大的原油运输船与 FSO Safer 一起排列，这艘油轮被联合国购买为 Nautica 号，现在更名为也门号。两艘船上的油箱将通过管道连接，并使用液压泵转移油。然后，Safer 将清除污泥（估计占原始货物的 5%），拖到附近的位置，并固定在一个用粗缆固定在海床上的特别加固的浮标上。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          edgetoedge
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/51567835-9b41-457f-8a84-214f2a299486.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>作业期间，两艘船需要在开放水域保持稳定，预计需要两周时间才能完成。已有 47 年历史的 Safer 上的管道和阀门严重腐蚀，增加了出现问题的风险。长时间静止后移动如此大量的石油也可能会极大地改变老化船体上的压力，从而导致船体破裂。自 2018 年以来，用于维持储油舱安全压力的系统一直无法运行，增加了发生事故的风险，最坏的情况包括爆炸。打捞队已向油罐中注入惰性气体，试图在石油被吸出之前稳定石油。</p><p>其他障碍包括天气。船员们面临着酷热的天气。此外，还有众所周知在该地区漂流的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/mines-port-damage-threaten-revival-of-sea-route-for-ukraine-grain-11656754200?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">水雷</a>，这是八年内战的副产品。</p><p>石油泄漏会破坏珍贵的珊瑚礁和红树林，并导致鱼类资源枯竭，估计需要 25 年才能恢复。它将暂时关闭附近的荷台达和萨利夫港口，这些港口是为数百万因战争而流离失所的人提供重要食品和救生用品的渠道。根据一项研究，为近 200 万人提供饮用水的海水淡化厂如果发生泄漏，也面临污染的风险<strong>&nbsp;</strong>斯坦福大学 Benjamin Q. Huynh 领导的一组研究人员发表了<strong>&nbsp;</strong>在科学杂志《自然》中。这可能会使持续存在的霍乱问题恶化。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/03656916-2320-43e3-b73e-12d9f0d09c80.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> “这确实是一场完美风暴，”联合国驻也门驻地协调员戴维·格雷斯利 (David Gressly) 说。 “我们真的别无选择，只能为此做点什么。”</p><p> 1,200 英尺高、日本制造的 Safer 于 1976 年下水，随后于 20 世纪 80 年代出售给也门政府，用于储存标记为出口的石油。八年前，伊朗支持的胡塞叛军在与沙特支持的港口城市亚丁政府作战时控制了附近的海岸线，之后该油轮被废弃，船上停泊着 110 万桶马里布轻质原油。</p><p>据联合国和外国政府称，自 2019 年以来，胡塞武装一直阻碍进入油轮的请求。外交官怀疑他们的目的是利用它在和平进程中获得让步，或者作为一枚浮动炸弹来阻止海上袭击。胡塞武装则表示，他们怀疑外国政府以“军事行动”为幌子，计划对他们采取军事行动。 <strong>&nbsp;</strong>防止漏油。</p><p>但在过去的一年里，沙特和胡塞武装的谈判代表在达成持久和平协议方面取得了进展，部分原因是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-brokered-deal-between-iran-saudi-arabia-marks-a-new-middle-east-d1eaf94e?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">沙特阿拉伯和伊朗之间的</a>地区局势更加缓和。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="517" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821583?width=700&amp;height=517" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">卫星图像显示“安全号”停泊在也门海岸附近。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：MAXAR TECHNOLOGIES/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>这一突破是在胡塞武装信任的一家也门公司的帮助下实现的。</p><p> Fahem 集团通过荷台达港进口粮食，该港还拥有一个粮仓和一家面粉厂。该集团于 2020 年开始试图说服胡塞武装，相信重大漏油事件将损害他们的经济和政治利益。该公司警告称，随着和平进程的进展，它将根除当地渔业，并关闭胡塞武装希望出口石油的港口。</p><p> “我们提出了也门海岸漏油情况的情景，”该公司首席执行官法蒂·法赫姆 (Fathi Fahem) 说。 “当我们详细解释这一点时，他们同意了我们的解决方案。”</p><p>该公司促成了胡塞武装和荷兰海事建设和维护公司 Boskalis 的子公司 SMIT Salvage 在首都萨那举行的会议。与此同时，联合国任命资深外交官格雷斯利来解决迫在眉睫的油轮危机，包括确保行动资金。</p><p> “Fahem 集团与驻地协调员一起的存在确实是一种新的体验，带来了相互信任，”侯赛因·埃齐说，</p>安萨尔阿拉外交部副部长，胡塞运动的正式名称。 <p></p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/caef4347-2641-42bf-b5b1-6effeb8d6e5e.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>经过一系列会议后，胡塞武装安全委员会和联合国于去年3月签署了一份谅解备忘录，将在18个月内将石油转移到替换油轮上。</p><p>一年多后的5月29日，包括40名打捞专家和SMIT的支持人员在内的65名船员从吉布提出发，开始了30个小时的航行，去寻找“Safer”号。</p><p>他们评估了哪些现有阀门和管道可用于将油泵出，并更换了有故障的部件，包括歧管。维持惰性气体所需的系统（其低含量的氧气可以防止易燃碳氢化合物气体的燃烧）已失效，因此工作人员将惰性气体泵入储罐以降低爆炸风险。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="3740" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/7026d3c8-ef5a-4b1c-afe7-4a22750453fb-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>一组潜水员检查了 Safer 的船体，以确保在石油输送开始后它不会破裂。</p><p> 7月16日，联合国购买的用于从Safer号装载石油的油轮抵达荷台达港口进行最后准备。该项目耗资 5500 万美元，是 1.43 亿美元的运营预算中最大的一笔支出，因为任何租赁公司都不愿意提供如此尺寸的船舶，因此必须这样做。迄今为止，联合国已从20多个国家筹集了1.21亿美元，其中主要包括沙特阿拉伯、荷兰、德国和美国，此外还有国际石油和天然气生产商协会和一些私人捐助者。</p><p>即使打捞作业安全结束，未来的冲突仍在酝酿，这次的冲突是谁真正拥有石油。</p><p>其中约 90% 的股份属于也门国家石油天然气公司 Sepoc，胡塞武装和亚丁国家政府均声称控制该公司。</p><p> “石油本身需要与萨那当局和政府进行单独讨论，”格雷斯利说。 “我们会一步一步地走下去。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-818938?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">联合国驻也门驻地协调员大卫·格雷斯利在红海的诺蒂卡号上。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Yahya Arhab/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>写信给 Sune Engel Rasmussen： <a href="mailto:sune.rasmussen@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">sune.rasmussen@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 22 Jul 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-race-to-avert-an-oil-spill-that-c​​ould-cost-20-billion-to-fix-85a884ea</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-race-to-avert-an-oil-spill-that-c​​ould-cost-20-billion-to-fix-85a884ea<author><![CDATA[Sune Engel Rasmussen]]></author><category> gfx-contrib</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>自然环境</category><category>环境污染</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>自然环境</category><category>环境污染</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[North Korea Launches Cruise Missiles Into Yellow Sea]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>平壤在美国核潜艇离开朝鲜半岛后不久进行了导弹试验<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001075434"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="574" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-822156?width=860&amp;height=574" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">韩国新闻报道了朝鲜周六最新的导弹发射，当时美国肯塔基号核潜艇离开朝鲜半岛。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：jung yeon-je/法新社/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001075434"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dasl-yoon" itemprop="url" rel="author">达斯尔·尹</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 22 日凌晨 2:33 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-launches-cruise-missiles-into-yellow-sea-405226a8"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>首尔——在一艘<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-nuclear-capable-boomer-sub-visits-south-korea-for-first-time-in-decades-dc4a8187?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">美国核潜艇离开朝鲜半岛</a>后不久，朝鲜发射了几枚巡航导弹，以展示其实力，以应对平壤的威胁。</p><p>据韩国参谋长联席会议称，朝鲜当地时间周六凌晨 4 点左右向黄海发射了多枚巡航导弹。首尔军方没有透露导弹是从哪里发射的，也没有透露导弹的飞行距离。</p><p>参谋长联席会议表示：“我们的军队加强了监视和警惕，同时与美国密切合作并保持坚定的战备态势。”</p><p>此次导弹发射是在俄亥俄级弹道导弹核潜艇肯塔基号周五从韩国出发之际进行的。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-to-send-its-biggest-sub-to-korean-peninsula-in-message-to-north-and-south-d998518?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">美国军舰</a>可以无限期地保持在水下状态，并可以向数千英里外的目标发射核弹头。它对朝鲜半岛的港口访问是<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-south-korea-pledge-cooperation-on-potential-use-of-nuclear-arms-ceeecec9?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">《华盛顿宣言》</a>的一部分，该宣言是拜登总统和韩国总统尹锡烈于四月下旬达成的协议。</p><p>在朝鲜日益严重的核威胁和导弹威胁的情况下，美国承诺向该地区派遣战略资产，以重申其保护盟友的承诺。周四，朝鲜警告称，此类核资产部署可能满足朝鲜使用核武器的条件。</p><p>朝鲜国防部长康善南在一份声明中表示：“美国军方必须认识到，它已经将其战略资产带入了过于危险的水域。”康表示，肯塔基号航空母舰的访问是对朝鲜的“直接核威胁”。韩国国防部否认平壤的指控，称潜艇访问和其他威慑措施是“对朝鲜持续的核和导弹威胁的公平防御反应”。</p><p>朝鲜最后一次<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-launches-two-cruise-missiles-from-submarine-8eb0dff1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">从潜艇发射巡航导弹</a>是在三月份。平壤官方媒体称，这次水下发射展示了该国实施核打击的多种方法。</p><p>本周早些时候，朝鲜发射了两枚短程弹道导弹，此前朝鲜发表了一系列批评华盛顿向朝鲜半岛派遣战略资产的声明。朝鲜一再拒绝与美国进行对话 周一，朝鲜领导人金正恩的妹妹<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/kim-jong-un">金与正</a>表示，平壤将寻求通过“充分运用武力”来遏制美国，并嘲笑了拜登政府的对话呼吁。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-soldiers-crossing-into-north-korea-points-to-security-gaps-576b7733?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">一名美国士兵周二在韩国一侧的联合安全区巡视期间越境进入朝鲜</a>后，美国官员试图通过多种渠道与朝鲜建立联系。朝鲜尚未做出回应。</p><p>尽管拜登政府一再提出无条件重返裁军谈判，但平壤没有表现出重返裁军谈判的兴趣。朝鲜正准备在 7 月 27 日庆祝一个被称为“胜利日”的重大节日。平壤可能会举行以军事装备为特色的阅兵式来庆祝这一节日。</p><p>写信给 Dasl Yoon，邮箱为<a href="mailto:dasl.yoon@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">dasl.yoon@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 22 Jul 2023 06:33:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-launches-cruise-missiles-into-yellow-sea-405226a8</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/north-korea-launches-cruise-missiles-into-yellow-sea-405226a8<author><![CDATA[Dasl Yoon]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>武装部队</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>武装部队</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Why America’s Largest Tool Company Couldn’t Make a Wrench in America]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>德克萨斯州的一家高度自动化工厂本应将工匠机械工具的制造带回美国海岸。这个耗资 9000 万美元的项目因设备问题和生产缓慢而注定失败。 <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821631/?width=1000&amp;size=0.8" alt="斯坦利百得 (Stanley Black &amp; Decker) 德克萨斯州制造的 Craftsman 棘轮扳手。该公司表示，将在破土动工 3.5 年后关闭沃斯堡工厂。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>斯坦利百得 (Stanley Black &amp; Decker) 德克萨斯州制造的 Craftsman 棘轮扳手。该公司表示，将在破土动工 3.5 年后关闭沃斯堡工厂。华尔街日报的埃文·詹金斯<span>华尔街日报的埃文·詹金斯</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001070397"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001070397"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/john-keilman" itemprop="url" rel="author">约翰·凯尔曼</a></span>埃文·詹金斯和<span class="author" itemprop="name">库珀·尼尔为《华尔街日报》</span>拍摄的照片</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 22 日上午 12:01（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/craftsman-america-wrench-stanley-black-decker-reshoring-factory-1125792f"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>世界上最大的工具公司不知道如何制造扳手。</p><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/SWK" class="company-name">斯坦利百得 (Stanley Black &amp; Decker)</a>在德克萨斯州沃思堡边缘建造了一座耗资 9,000 万美元的工厂，旨在以前所未有的效率锻造机械工具，为 Craftsman 品牌增添美国制造的光彩。但自动化系统却失败了，原本应该大量生产的工具却很难找到，以至于有些人认为它们是收藏品。</p><p>今年三月，即破土动工 3.5 年后，斯坦利宣布将关闭工厂。该房产目前正在发布出售广告。</p><p> Craftsman 工厂是美国制造商努力将离岸工厂带回国内的一个引人注目的例子。政府的激励措施和缩短供应链的愿望引发了工厂建设热潮。美国劳动力成本高昂，自动化对于工厂盈利至关重要。</p><p>将手动任务交给机器，机器应该以最少的人力参与和最大的生产率来生产商品，这本身也带来了挑战。 Craftsman 工厂首创的系统本应能够如此高效地制造工具，从而使成本与中国持平，但前员工表示，在公司决定终止之前，该系统存在无法解决的问题。</p><p> “它应该是不同的，”在工厂担任电镀工程师的汤姆·费尔蒂说。 “它本来应该让 Craftsman 品牌回归。这就是所有这些新技术。这就是为什么我从北卡罗来纳州搬到德克萨斯州成为其中的一部分，这绝对是一场灾难。”</p><p>斯坦利呼应了之前的声明，将工厂的关闭归咎于几个因素。</p><p> “我们致力于以创新的方式制造 Craftsman 机械工具，”一位发言人说道。 “新冠疫情和供应链挑战，加上技术未能达到我们的预期，导致运营中断。”</p><p>该公司拒绝进一步置评。</p><p>此次关闭标志着这家总部位于康涅狄格州新不列颠的工具制造商的转变，该公司在过去 14 年的大部分时间里都在追求增长。 Stanley 于 2010 年与 Black &amp; Decker 合并，并于 2017 年收购了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NWL" class="company-name">Newell Brands</a>的工具部门。这一热潮使该公司变成了一个庞然大物，使其收入从 2009 年的 37 亿美元增至去年的近 170 亿美元。</p><p> Craftsman 占该总额超过 10 亿美元，是扩张的关键部分。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819957?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">斯坦利百得 (Stanley Black &amp; Decker) 位于德克萨斯州沃思堡的 Craftsman 工厂现已关闭。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：库珀·尼尔为《华尔街日报》拍摄</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>几十年来，它一直是西尔斯的旗舰品牌，与美国制造商签订合同，生产扳手、棘轮和套筒等机械工具。这些工具是美国家庭和车库的固定装置，但在西尔斯通过<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/stanley-to-make-more-craftsman-tools-in-u-s-11557919800?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">将生产转移到中国</a>来削减成本后，爱好者们表示产品质量下降了。例如，一些工匠扳手用额外的金属加固其开口端，这使得它们很难在狭小的空间中使用。这为它们赢得了一个可笑的绰号“龙虾爪”。</p><p> Stanley 于 2017 年以 9 亿美元收购了 Craftsman，当时的首席执行官 James Loree 表示，这笔交易提供了该品牌“重新美国化”的机会。该公司开始在其美国工厂组装 Craftsman 卷尺、空气压缩机和其他产品，并在包装​​上贴上红、白、蓝色标志，上面写着“美国制造，采用全球材料”。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="900" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821194?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>沃斯堡工厂于 2019 年宣布成立，旨在更进一步，用美国钢材锻造该品牌标志性的扳手、棘轮和套筒，以满足消费者对美国制造工具的渴望。高管们表示，自动化和其他先进制造技术将使该工厂能够在成本上与进口产品竞争。</p><p>斯坦利时任全球运营副总裁史蒂夫·斯塔夫斯特罗姆 (Steve Stafstrom) 表示，这需要设计一种能够将劳动力和材料效率提高到远远超出标准的系统。</p><p> “我们有一群人非常致力于使其发挥作用，”他说。 “我们必须想出以前从未使用过的技术。”</p><p> Stanley 已经在德克萨斯州法默斯布兰奇附近的一家工厂为优质 MAC 和 Proto 品牌生产机械工具。前员工表示，大部分工作都是手动完成的，这是行业标准。工人们用钳子调整一块热金属，然后用压力机将其压成扳手或棘轮的形状，并用手将工具从一台机器移动到另一台机器。</p><p>斯坦利对 Craftsman 工厂的计划集中于大部分流程的自动化，正如一家提供部分机械的白俄罗斯公司上传的 YouTube<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uZwIPYcZ_yU" target="_blank" class="icon none">视频</a>中所见。</p><p>通过类似断头台的装置将一根称为钢坯的钢条从卷材上切下来，然后通过传送带传送通过加热器。一台机器将发光的红色坯料卷成类似棒棒糖的形状，然后机器人将其放置在压力机上，机械手指将其移动通过几个工位，直到将其敲打成完全成型的棘轮。</p><p>视频显示成堆未完成的棘轮和扳手，上面几乎没有任何多余的金属。前工人表示，自动化方法的产量应该远远高于传统的工具制造工艺，在传统的工具制造工艺中，钢坯的一半以上的钢材被修剪掉。</p><p>高管们在斯坦利 2019 年 5 月投资者日上表示，该工厂将在 18 个月内投产。前员工表示，由于大流行而推迟了时间表，这意味着该系统在扩大规模之前没有经过适当的测试。</p><p>一位前运营负责人表示，对白俄罗斯制造的滚压机的调整有时需要从海外发送新的工具，这可能需要数周时间。他和其他前雇员表示，扳手和棘轮在媒体上变得畸形。他说，一种解决办法是要求机器以一半的产能运行，但这会降低工厂的成本效益。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819954?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">电镀工程师汤姆·费尔蒂在他的家中。 “他们花费了数百万美元试图让这些机器运转起来，”他说。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：库珀·尼尔为《华尔街日报》拍摄</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>“他们花费了数百万美元试图让这些机器正常运转，”电镀工程师费尔蒂说。</p><p>记者未能联系到白俄罗斯公司 AMT Engineering 置评。</p><p>工厂的其他部分也存在问题。从事热处理工作的杰里米·谢弗 (Jeremy Scheffer) 表示，有时候，到达他所在部门的插座上带有尚未完全冲孔的金属，或者上面没有印上工匠的名字。</p><p>于 2021 年退休的斯塔夫斯特罗姆表示，工厂的困境因对工具制造有深入了解的“白发人”的流失而加剧，而费尔蒂则表示，斯坦利工具部门高层的人员流动也是其中之一。</p><p>宣布建厂时，该公司全球工具和存储总裁杰弗里·安塞尔 (Jeffrey Ansell) 于 2020 年离职，此后由其他四名高管接任。记者未能联系到他置评。</p><p>尽管存在这些问题，模具设计师 Greg Heltne 表示，工人们仍然制造了数千个套筒。但他和其他前工人表示，零售商不希望它们没有工厂生产的棘轮和扳手。</p><p> “当顾客说，‘我想要我订购的所有东西’而我们无法交付时，我们无能为力，”Heltne 说。</p><p> Craftsman 的主要零售合作伙伴之一 Lowe&#39;s 拒绝置评。其他销售该品牌的零售商，包括 Ace Hardware、Amazon.com、Blain&#39;s Farm &amp; Fleet 和 Atwoods Ranch &amp; Home Goods 均未回应置评请求。</p><p>前工人表示，工厂里库存积压。谢弗说，当高层管理人员和董事会成员来访时，他和他的同事被告知重新排列未完成的插座箱，这样它们就不会那么引人注目。</p><p> “有很多大张旗鼓，很多大人物都在检查工厂，”模具工程师罗尼·科顿 (Ronnie Cotton) 说。 “他们只是想展示某种进步，但最终却未能正常发挥作用。”</p><p>在美国生产机械工具的竞争对手公司表示，他们的工厂生产线已部分自动化，但仍然严重依赖工人的技能。</p><p> “制造这些扳手的人的艺术性非常重要，”Wright Tool 总裁 Tom Futey 说道，该公司在俄亥俄州巴伯顿生产高端工具。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          edgetoedge
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/f1a84adb-236f-43cb-9dd5-5a15e3445bea.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>另一个高端品牌 Snap-on 的首席执行官尼克·平丘克 (Nick Pinchuk) 表示，2010 年该公司美国工厂的工人与机器人的比例约为 100 比 1。他说，现在的比例是 8 比 1，但逐步过渡帮助公司确定了人类和机器的最佳角色。</p><p> “有时，安装自动化的难易程度被高估了一点，”他说。 “它从何而来，人们一开始并不真正了解产品是如何制造的。”</p><p>麻省理工学院教授兼机器人专家 Julie Shah 表示，人们往往拥有机器无法比拟的专业知识和灵活性。她回忆起一家航空航天公司询问是否可以自动化一名拥有数十年以精确和多种方式热处理部件的经验的员工的工作。</p><p> “当你深入研究它时，你会想，‘不，这是一个计算极其复杂的问题，’”她说。 “人们很容易低估某人在看似相当简单的任务中的判断力和经验。”</p><p>当工具爱好者想知道 Craftsman 德克萨斯州制造的产品何时上市时，该公司的社交媒体账户一再做出保证。 2022 年 6 月，斯坦利的 Twitter 账户表示，该工厂正在“为开业做准备”，并计划再雇用 100 名员工。</p><p>那时，斯坦利已经宣布剥离其安全业务、石油和天然气部门以及制门部门，以成为一家更加专注的公司。 2022 年 7 月的财报电话会议显示，核心工具业务在疫情繁荣时期后遭遇需求突然下降。</p><p>斯坦利股价暴跌，裁员成为当务之急，因为该公司试图削减超过 60 亿美元的库存。去年就任首席执行官的小唐纳德·艾伦 (Donald Allan Jr.) 表示，公司将削减 30% 的设施，并将销售的产品数量减少 40%，以削减 20 亿美元的成本。</p><p>一些前员工表示，在斯坦利开始裁员之前，Craftsman 工厂似乎更接近解决生产问题。赫尔特纳说，他和一位同事去年 12 月被解雇了。</p><p>该工厂从未达到计划的 500 名员工数量，3 月份斯坦利宣布关闭时，员工数量减少至 175 人。 The company said the same day that it was closing a plant in Cheraw, SC, that had 182 employees who made utility knives and portable storage units, folding those operations into other factories. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="1050" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-819955?width=700&amp;height=1050" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Tooling designer Greg Heltne said he was laid off from the Fort Worth factory this past December.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Cooper neill for the wall street journal</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Cheraw Town Manager Robert Wolfe said a few Stanley workers remain in the plant, and no buyer has materialized. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/CWK" class="">Cushman &amp; Wakefield</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> the real-estate firm selling the Fort Worth factory, said no deal has closed on that property.</p><p> Craftsman mechanics&#39; tools continue to be made in Asia, according to their packaging. Former Stanley employees said those plants have some automation but still rely on manual processing.</p><p> Allan told an investor conference in May that the company has opened new plants in Mexico to serve the North American market, and that Stanley aimed to reduce its manufacturing presence in Asia. He didn&#39;t specify the brands or tool lines that would be included in the shift.</p><p> Goldman Sachs analyst Joe Ritchie said that the shutdown of the Fort Worth plant is a minor issue in Stanley&#39;s overall business. Shoppers likely will take it in stride if the tools continue to be made overseas, he said, and investors are focused on the broader cost-reduction plan. Shares are up about 27% since the start of the year.</p><p> Some consumers, though, were infuriated. Jeff King, a former tech executive who hosts a YouTube review show called the Den of Tools, said his viewers&#39; excitement about once-beloved tools returning to US production curdled into a feeling that they were misled.</p><p> “Other companies didn&#39;t make promises to bring manufacturing back to the US,” he said. “Craftsman did.”</p><p> Stanley had predicted the factory would make 60 million tools annually, but ex-employees said in the weeks after the shutdown that they weren&#39;t sure if anything had made it to store shelves. By summer, though, domestically manufactured Craftsman socket sets began to appear at retailers.</p><p> A Wall Street Journal reporter on Monday bought an 88-piece set straight out of the shipping box at a Lowe&#39;s in suburban Chicago. The bright red case was embossed with stars and stripes, and inside was a cardboard placard that read, “Forged in Texas.” The set cost $89.98, less than half of what some <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/EBAY" class="company-name">eBay</a> vendors were seeking.</p><p> “LIMITED QTY never to be seen again,” wrote a seller who posted an identical set for $189.99.</p><p> Wisconsin carpenter Eric Jacobi got two sets through an online store that serves the military. A spokeswoman for the Army &amp; Air Force Exchange Service said it had acquired 1,200 produced for a retailer that backed out of its purchase.</p><p> Jacobi, who runs a Craftsman fan group on Facebook, said the tools felt sturdier than their Taiwan-made equivalents, though some sockets were overly shallow and not entirely chrome plated.</p><p> Given their imperfect state and apparent scarcity, he worried that using them could damage their value as a collectible, so he heeded an online follower who advised that he lock the tools away.</p><p> “I don&#39;t think I ever will touch these,” he said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
        "><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4> A brief history of the wrench </h4><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="509" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821773?width=700&amp;height=509" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> &#39;Cut-out&#39; wrenches carry the names of companies whose equipment they were made to service, and are now prized by collectors.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Don Haury</p></figcaption></figure><ul class="articleList"><li> An iron nut found in a Roman archaeological dig suggested that wrenches were being used as early as the first century AD, according to the book “Ancient Carpenters&#39; Tools.”</li><li> Some of the first published images of wrenches appeared in Diderot&#39;s Encyclopedia, published in 1771.</li><li> American workers of the early 19th century made their own crude wrenches by bending a bar of iron. Blacksmiths forged other versions until commercial production took over in the mid-19th century.</li><li> Farm-equipment manufacturers made customized wrenches to service their machines, said Don Haury, who owns more than 10,000 of the tools.</li><li> During World War II, propaganda artists used the wrench as a symbol of America&#39;s manufacturing might.</li><li> The once-freewheeling design of wrenches has coalesced into metric and fractional sizes. That standardization of wrench sizes didn&#39;t happen in the US until 1929, Haury said. </li></ul><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="518" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821765?width=700&amp;height=518" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Wrenches figured prominently in some World War II propaganda posters.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Corbis/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div></div><p> Write to John Keilman at <a href="mailto:john.keilman@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">john.keilman@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 22 Jul 2023 04:01:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/craftsman-america-wrench-stanley-black-decker-reshoring-factory-1125792f</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/craftsman-america-wrench-stanley-black-decker-reshoring-factory-1125792f<author><![CDATA[John Keilman]]></author><category> wsjexchange</category><category> photo-commission</category><category> WSJ公司</category><category>leder</category><category> exchangecover</category><category> Metal Products</category><category> Cutlery/Hand Tools</category><category> Consumer Goods</category><category> Durable Household Products</category><category> Houseware</category><category>工业品</category><category>Capacity/Facilities</category><category> Automation</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Stanley Black &amp; Decker</category><category> SWK</category><category> capacity</category><category> facilities</category><category> automation</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>metal products</category><category> cutlery</category><category> hand tools</category><category> consumer goods</category><category> durable household products</category><category> houseware</category><category>工业品</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Brazil Cracks Down on Gun Owners]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>总统路易斯·伊纳西奥·卢拉·达席尔瓦发誓要扭转右翼前任领导下的枪支泛滥现象<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001074310"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="572" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821835?width=860&amp;height=572" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">巴西总统路易斯·伊纳西奥·卢拉·达席尔瓦自一月份上任以来已通过了多项措施来控制枪支所有权。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：marcelo camargo/讲义/Shutterstock </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001074310"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/samantha-pearson" itemprop="url" rel="author">萨曼莎·皮尔森 卢西亚娜</a></span>·马加拉斯</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 21 日下午 4:02 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/brazil-cracks-down-on-gun-owners-c8faf1d3"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>圣保罗——巴西总统路易斯·伊纳西奥·卢拉·达席尔瓦周五通过了一项加强枪支管制的法令，这是继右翼前任雅伊尔·博尔索纳罗领导下的枪支<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/brazil-moves-to-take-back-guns-after-surge-in-purchases-87a06cdd?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">购买激增</a>之后，他最近努力从拉丁美洲最大国家的街道上清除枪支。</p><p>达席尔瓦在总统府举行的仪式上签署了该法令，承诺“让国家恢复正常”，将巴西人可以购买的自卫枪支数量从四支减少到两支，每年的弹药津贴从200发子弹减少到50发，并禁止24小时射击俱乐部。</p><p>自达席尔瓦一月份上任以来，该法令还采取了一系列其他措施来<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/brazils-new-president-reverses-his-predecessors-loosened-gun-laws-11672693693?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">控制枪支所有权</a>，其中包括在他就任总统几个小时后就通过的禁止携带已装弹武器的禁令。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>枪支管制在巴西已成为一个严重分歧的问题，该国<a href="https://www.wsj.com/graphics/how-does-your-city-compare-to-latin-american-violence/?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">枪支犯罪猖獗</a>，截至 2017 年，该国的凶杀案数量比世界上任何地方都多，而且大多是使用枪支实施的。</p><p>虽然达席尔瓦的左翼工人党和许多犯罪专家认为，减少流通的枪支数量将减少枪支犯罪，但博尔索纳罗和右翼政治团体则认为，巴西人应该有权<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/brazil-has-an-idea-to-fix-rampant-gun-violence-more-guns-11546315200?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">保护自己</a>免受该国全副武装的犯罪分子的侵害。</p><p>达席尔瓦在周五的一次演讲中表示：“我们将继续努力解除巴西的武装——应该武装的是警察和武装部队。”他在演讲中还宣布了加强亚马逊地区贩毒路线沿线警务的措施。</p><p> “我们不能允许人们积累武器库，”他说。达席尔瓦说：“我们不能确定这些枪支只卖给正派和诚实的人，这些人只是想要一把枪来保护自己。”他补充说，他担心宽松的枪支法会让犯罪分子更容易武装自己。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821721?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">达席尔瓦的法令强制射击俱乐部在晚上 10 点关闭，而不是全天候营业。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：马蒂亚斯·德拉克罗瓦/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>根据新法令，购买枪支用于狩猎的巴西人将可以拥有六支枪，而不是之前的 30 支。在博尔索纳罗的领导下，猎人的枪支销量猛增，引发了反枪支活动人士的批评，他们认为，在一个猎杀野猪以外的动物是非法的国家，向猎人提供这么多枪支毫无意义。</p><p>政府表示，以前将射击作为一项运动的巴西人每年最多可以购买 15 万发子弹，而现在在某些情况下只能购买到 4,000 发子弹。该法令还禁止使用某些枪支，例如 9 毫米手枪，并强制射击俱乐部在晚上 10 点关闭，而不是全天候营业。</p><p>在博尔索纳罗的领导下，枪支拥有者只要在前往射击俱乐部的途中就可以携带已装弹的枪支。巴西司法部长弗拉维奥·迪诺表示，他怀疑一些俱乐部继续营业只是为了给会员提供合法借口，让他们可以在白天或晚上随时携带上膛的武器。</p><p> “你会在凌晨两点用上了膛的武器逮捕一个人，他会说他正在去射击俱乐部的路上，”迪诺周五在仪式结束后接受电视采访时说。</p><p>但巴西的许多枪支拥有者表示，政府的镇压是不公平的。</p><p> “这对这项运动来说很糟糕，”戈亚斯州中部一家枪支配件商店的店主古斯塔沃·马里亚诺说。 “在靶场一天，一个人可以发射一千发子弹，这些规则使它不可行。”</p><p>枪支俱乐部老板古斯塔沃·帕齐尼表示，如果巴西人无法训练如何正确射击，那么他们最终将受到犯罪分子的摆布。 “没有射击俱乐部，就没有运动……而犯罪分子却仍然装备精良。”</p><p>写信给 Samantha Pearson（ <a href="mailto:samantha.pearson@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">samantha.pearson@wsj.com）</a>和 Luciana Magalhaes（ <a href="mailto:luciana.magalhaes@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">luciana.magalhaes@wsj.com</a> ）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 20:02:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/brazil-cracks-down-on-gun-owners-c8faf1d3</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/brazil-cracks-down-on-gun-owners-c8faf1d3<author><![CDATA[Samantha Pearson]]></author><category>突击</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>枪支控制</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>射击</category><category>社会问题</category><category>运动的</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>日常新闻</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>路易斯·伊纳西奥·卢拉·达席尔瓦</category><category>突击</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>枪支控制</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>射击</category><category>社会问题</category><category>运动的</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>常规新闻</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Russia Arrests Militant Right-Wing Critic Igor Girkin in Widening Crackdown]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>克里姆林宫在多年镇压倾向西方的领导人后向民族主义者和军事领导人施加压力<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001073978"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821729?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">伊戈尔·吉尔金周五在莫斯科被拘留，并被指控犯有极端主义罪。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：alexander zemlianichenko/新闻池</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001073978"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/alan-cullison" itemprop="url" rel="author">艾伦·卡里森</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/thomas-grove" itemprop="url" rel="author">托马斯·格罗夫</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 21 日下午 2:34 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-arrests-militant-right-wing-critic-igor-girkin-in-widening-crackdown-3b6308"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>俄罗斯调查人员周五逮捕了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/vladimir-putin">弗拉基米尔·普京</a>总统的一位著名右翼批评者，这是对公开宣称的俄罗斯爱国者的更广泛镇压，这些爱国者攻击普京未能以足够的力度<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/blasts-hit-military-base-in-russian-occupied-crimea-c9c1ffc1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在乌克兰进行战争</a>。</p><p>伊戈尔·吉尔金 (Igor Girkin) 是一位强烈的民族主义人物，也是俄罗斯支持的乌克兰东部武装分子的前领导人，据他的妻子称，他被拘留在莫斯科的公寓中，并被指控犯有极端主义罪，她在这位前军官受欢迎的 Telegram 频道上宣布了对他的拘留。国营塔斯社证实了他的被捕。</p><p>普京多年来一直镇压左翼和西倾反对者，以维护其23年的统治，但在上个月末准军事领导人叶夫根尼·普里戈任领导的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/wagner-prigozhin-putin-mutiny-moscow-march-7072d6ea?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">兵变之后</a>，他也开始镇压右翼批评者，这些批评者因他入侵乌克兰而变得更加大胆。</p><p>其中化名斯特雷科夫在乌克兰东部写作和活动的吉尔金因对普京的严厉批评而脱颖而出，但他最新的评论似乎越界了。</p><p>最近，他在 Telegram 频道上发帖称普京是一个“无足轻重的人”，他设法“把灰尘扔到俄罗斯人民的眼睛里”。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>吉尔金显然是指明年的俄罗斯总统选举，届时预计普京将寻求连任六年，吉尔金写道，“这个国家将无法在这种懦弱的平庸政权的统治下再存活六年。”</p><p>吉尔金的被捕立即激怒了民族主义圈子，他们赞扬了他针对普京<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/putin-has-been-humiliated-put-under-pressure-u-k-spy-chief-says-894d62c2?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">笨手笨脚地入侵</a>乌克兰的愤怒信件。</p><p>吉尔金的一名同胞试图在他被拘留的法庭外举行抗议。与吉尔金一起创立民族主义愤怒爱国者俱乐部（KRP）的帕维尔·古巴列夫（Pavel Gubarev）表示，吉尔金“从一开始就正确地批评了国防部的行动”。法院下令将 Girkin 关押至 9 月 18 日举行的下一次听证会。</p><p>民族主义活动家格奥尔基·费奥多罗夫称吉尔金被捕是更广泛镇压的先兆。</p><p>他写道：“这是一个非常坏的消息，意味着镇压不仅针对KRP成员，而且针对整个活跃的爱国社区，这显然对最高权力来说已经变得危险。” “我们必须团结起来支持斯特列科夫，因为这只是开始。”</p><p>自从6月24日普里戈任在莫斯科发生兵变和游行失败后，俄罗斯当局开始在军队中清洗可能同情这位准军事领导人及其私人军事连的军官。</p><p>虽然吉尔金对国防部长谢尔盖·绍伊古和总参谋长瓦列里·格拉西莫夫将军的批评与普里戈任的批评相呼应，但他的拘留是一系列与叛变无关的现任和退休军官中最新的一个，这表明克里姆林宫正在对那些涉嫌分裂忠诚的人采取更广泛的措施。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821750?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">六月兵变后，俄罗斯总统弗拉基米尔·普京开始镇压右翼批评者。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：SPUTNIK/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>本月早些时候，乌克兰南部的一名俄罗斯高级指挥官因批评军方领导层对战争的管理而被免职。在泄露的录音带中，伊万·波波夫少将表示，他因向军事领导人说实话而被免职，其中包括直接控制俄罗斯乌克兰战争的格拉西莫夫。</p><p>本周早些时候，俄罗斯当局还对退役上校提出指控。</p>吉尔金在本周早些时候的 Telegram 帖子中写道，前军事情报官员弗拉基米尔·克瓦奇科夫 (Vladimir Kvachkov) 曾因 2009 年企图武装叛乱的指控而入狱。10 年后他被释放，但现在面临着抹黑军队的新指控。<p></p><p> 2014年普京占领克里米亚后，吉尔金成为俄罗斯极端民族主义者和民族统一主义者的象征，当时吉尔金领导一群俄罗斯支持的民兵占领了乌克兰城市斯拉维扬斯克。他很快就以残酷的手段和即决处决而闻名。</p><p>他升任​​为俄罗斯支持的顿涅茨克分裂主义小国的假定国防部长，叛军击落马来西亚航空公司一架民用航班、机上 298 名乘客和机组人员全部遇难时，他就担任了这个职务。去年，吉尔金和另外两名武装分子被荷兰法院判定犯有大规模谋杀罪。他否认对此负有责任。</p><p>逃往俄罗斯后，吉尔金一直指责克里姆林宫未能以足够的力度进行对乌克兰的战争，包括他支持的去年的入侵。</p><p>写信给 Alan Cullison <a href="mailto:alan.cullison@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">(alan.cullison@wsj.com)</a>和 Thomas Grove ( <a href="mailto:thomas.grove@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">thomas.grove@wsj.com</a> )</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 18:34:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ Russia-arrests-militant-right-wing-critic-igor-girkin-in-widening-crackdown-3b6308</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ Russia-arrests-militant-right-wing-critic-igor-girkin-in-widening-crackdown-3b6308<author><![CDATA[Alan CullisonThomas Grove]]></author><category>乌克兰</category><category>华尔街日报</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>Terrorism</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>Ukraine</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>伊戈尔·吉尔金</category><category>弗拉基米尔普京</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>terrorism</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[U.S. to Send More Warships, Marines to Middle East Amid Rising Tensions With Iran]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>过去三个月，华盛顿向该地区派遣了部队，阻止伊朗军队针对商船<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001072734"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="688" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821405?width=860&amp;height=688" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">监控视频拍摄的图像显示，上个月，三艘伊朗船只靠近霍尔木兹海峡的一艘商船。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：美国海军/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001072734"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/dion-nissenbaum" itemprop="url" rel="author">迪昂·尼森鲍姆</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 7 月 21 日中午 12:22（东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-sending-more-warships-marines-to-middle-east-amid-rising-tensions-with-iran-dfc3a048"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>美国军方表示，正在向中东派遣更多军舰和海军陆战队员，以阻止伊朗在该地区扣押更多船只。</p><p>五角大楼周四晚间表示，在美国海军挫败了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/iran-tried-to-seize-two-oil-tankers-near-strait-of-hormuz-u-s-navy-says-4be301e1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">伊朗本月早些时候在阿曼湾国际水域扣押两艘油轮的企图</a>后，国防部长劳埃德·奥斯汀下令向该地区增派新部队。一名美国军方官员表示，此举并不是针对特定的新威胁，而是针对伊朗的行动。</p><p>中东盟友一直敦促美国采取更多措施对抗伊朗，伊朗在今年春天的一周内扣押了两艘油轮，其中一艘将科威特原油运往休斯敦，供<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/CVX" class="">雪佛龙</a>公司使用<span class="company-name-type">。</span></p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-pressured-to-secure-persian-gulf-after-iran-seizes-tankers-7bab70cb?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">阿拉伯联合酋长国对美国对今年早些时候伊朗扣押油轮事件缺乏回应表示特别失望</a>，并呼吁五角大楼向波斯湾派遣更多部队。</p><p>过去三个月，美国向中东派遣了一系列部队，阻止伊朗军队干扰通过该地区的商船。</p><p> 4月初，在伊朗扣押两艘油轮之前，美国<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-sends-submarine-to-middle-east-in-show-of-force-441dbb42?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">派出一艘导弹潜艇</a>进入红海。扣押事件发生后，美国向该地区派遣了一艘导弹驱逐舰，并使用侦察机密切监视阿曼湾一艘油轮周围的伊朗海军活动。</p><p>即使有新的动向，美国在中东的军事存在仍将远远小于伊拉克和阿富汗战争期间部署的兵力，因为五角大楼近年来一直寻求将战略重点转向中国和俄罗斯。但伊朗的行动，包括最近对波斯湾航运的威胁，促使五角大楼将部队转移回中东。</p><p>此外，俄罗斯喷气式战斗机加大了对叙利亚上空美国飞机的骚扰力度，美国官员表示，这似乎是莫斯科向美国施压，迫使其从该地区撤军。美国官员表示，伊朗人也有同样的目标。</p><p>负责监督美国在叙利亚以及中东和东南亚其他 20 个国家上空的军事行动的空军中将亚历克苏斯·格林克维奇 (Alexus Grynkewich) 上个月表示，“伊朗人当然希望联军撤离叙利亚，这样他们就可以有行动自由，让伊朗结盟团体为了自己的目的而在叙利亚各地运送先进的常规武器和致命能力。”</p><p>迄今为止，美国威慑伊朗的努力收效有限。</p><p>本月早些时候，美国海军挫败了伊朗军队两次分别扣押两艘商业油轮的企图。海军表示，第二天，伊朗军队确实扣押了第三艘涉嫌走私石油的商船。对于这种情况，美国海军表示没有干预。</p><p>美国现在正在采取更多措施来对抗伊朗。本周早些时候， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-deploys-advanced-f-35-jets-destroyer-to-middle-east-to-brush-back-iranian-forces-7d9a92cf?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">五角大楼表示将向该地区派遣最先进的喷气式战斗机</a>——F-35。现在，五角大楼正在派遣一个海军陆战队两栖战备小组和海军陆战队远征部队，其中至少有两艘舰艇和最多 2,500 名海军陆战队员。</p><p>美国中央司令部司令、陆军上将埃里克·库里拉表示，新部队将有助于“保障国际商业的自由流动……维护基于规则的国际秩序，并阻止伊朗在该地区破坏稳定的活动。”</p><p>美国军方表示，过去两年，伊朗已针对该地区近20艘商船进行攻击。</p><p>美国对抗伊朗的努力超出了波斯湾。今年三月，五角大楼<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-strikes-iranian-backed-group-in-syria-after-drone-attack-kills-one-american-and-wounds-six-9f3dafe6?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">针对叙利亚境内伊朗支持的武装分子进行了空袭</a>，以应对无人机袭击叙利亚境内美国基地并造成一名美国承包商死亡的事件。</p><p>美国官员表示，美国的袭击迫使伊朗缩减了针对该地区美军的企图。但伊朗反而加大了针对波斯湾商船的攻击力度，全球超过三分之一的海运原油都在此过境。</p><p>写信给迪昂·尼森鲍姆 (Dion Nissenbaum)： <a href="mailto:dion.nissenbaum@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">dion.nissenbaum@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 16:22:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-sending-more-warships-marines-to-middle-east-amid-rising-tensions-with-iran-dfc3a048</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-sending-more-warships-marines-to-middle-east-amid-rising-tensions-with-iran-dfc3a048<author><![CDATA[Dion Nissenbaum]]></author><category>活力</category><category>军用船只</category><category>航空航天/国防</category><category>国防设备/产品</category><category>化石燃料</category><category>工业品</category><category>油和气</category><category>油</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>武装部队</category><category>海军</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>武装部队</category><category>海军</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>活力</category><category>军用船只</category><category>航天</category><category>防御</category><category>国防装备</category><category>产品</category><category>化石燃料</category><category>工业品</category><category>油和气</category><category>油</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Rise and Fall of the Chief Diversity Officer]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>随着公司优先事项的转变，多元化高管纷纷退出； “一切都是一场战斗” <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001071159"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820139?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">左起：Melinda Starbird，人力资源和多元化主管；丹尼·门罗 (Dani Monroe)，麻省布里格姆将军医院前任 CDO；和 Yelp 的 CDO 米里亚姆·沃伦 (Miriam Warren)。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片插图：Melinda Starbird、Cheryl Richard、Yelp </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001071159"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/te-ping-chen" itemprop="url" rel="author">：陈德平</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/lauren-weber" itemprop="url" rel="author">劳伦·韦伯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">Updated July 21, 2023 12:06 pm ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chief-diversity-officer-cdo-business-corporations-e110a82f"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>两年前，首席多元化官是高管队伍中最炙手可热的员工之一。现在，他们越来越感到被冷落。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/NFLX" class="">Netflix</a> <span class="company-name-type">、</span><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/DIS" class="company-name">迪士尼</a>和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/WBD" class="company-name">华纳兄弟探索</a>公司等公司最近表示，备受瞩目的多元化、公平和包容性高管将离职。自去年以来，数千名注重多元化的员工被解雇，一些公司正在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/diversity-workplace-affirmative-action-dei-3646683b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">缩减</a>种族正义承诺。</p><p>去年秋天科技行业的洗牌期间，许多公司开始重新审视其高管队伍，之后多元化、公平性和包容性（DEI）工作就成为了人们关注的焦点。一些首席多元化官员表示，自从最高法院<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/supreme-court-rules-against-affirmative-action-c94b5a9c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">驳回大学招生中的平权行动</a>以及公司准备迎接<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/republican-attorneys-general-warn-top-u-s-businesses-over-discrimination-1eb78d29?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">潜在的法律挑战</a>以来，他们的工作正面临更多审查。 DEI工作也成为了一个<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ron-desantiss-education-policies-leave-florida-teachers-feeling-unsure-3a81a236?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noreferrer noopener">政治目标</a>。</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/YELP" class="">Yelp</a>首席多元化官米里亚姆·沃伦 (Miriam Warren) 在谈到该<span class="company-name-type">领域</span>高管面临的挑战时表示：“悲伤、非常疲倦，甚至在某些情况下甚至不知所措”。 Warren says the fear that company commitments are imperiled fuel her and others to feel “more committed to the work than ever.” Yelp&#39;s DEI budget has grown for the past five years.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>在采访中，现任和前任首席多元化官表示，公司高管有时不想改变招聘或晋升流程，尽管最初告诉首席数据官他们被聘用是为了改善人才管道。这种迅速的转变表明，公司对多元化举措的热情并不总是持久的，这让一些多元化官员现在对他们的职业道路产生了质疑。</p><p> 2020 年 5 月，乔治·弗洛伊德 (George Floyd) 在警方拘留期间被谋杀后，各公司纷纷聘请首席多元化官，从而改变了最高管理层的面貌。猎头公司 Russell Reynolds 的一项研究显示，2018 年，标准普尔 500 指数中只有不到一半的公司聘用了该职位，而到 2022 年，四分之三的公司已经设立了该职位。</p><p>曾经主要负责人力资源事务的多元化领导者现在预计将参与新产品开发、营销工作以及影响工人和消费者感受的时事。沃伦和其他 CDO 表示，扩大的职权范围是在政治分裂的环境中实施的，在这种环境中，企业多元化努力经常成为<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/companies-new-cause-dodging-the-culture-wars-73e52cf3?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">社交媒体风暴</a>的主题。</p><h3>需求下降</h3><p>New analysis from employment data provider Live Data Technologies shows that chief diversity officers have been more vulnerable to layoffs than their human resources counterparts, experiencing 40% higher turnover. Their job searches are also taking longer.</p><p> “I got to 300 applications and then I stopped tracking,” says Stephanie Lubin, who was laid off from her role as diversity head at Drizly, an online alcohol marketplace, in May following the company&#39;s acquisition by <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/UBER" class="">Uber</a> <span class="company-name-type">.</span></p> In one case, Lubin says she went through 16 rounds of interviews for a role she didn&#39;t get, and says she is now planning to pivot out of DEI work.<p></p><p> The number of CDO searches is down 75% in the past year, says Jason Hanold, chief executive of Hanold Associates Executive Search, which works with Fortune 100 companies to recruit HR and DEI executives, among other roles. Demand is the lowest he has seen in his 30 years of recruiting.</p><p> At the same time, he says, more executives are feeling skittish about taking on diversity roles.</p><p> “They&#39;re telling us, the only way I want to go into another role with DEI is if it includes something else,” he says of the requests for broader titles that offer more responsibilities and resources. He estimates that 60% of diversity roles he is currently filling combine the title with another position, such as chief human resources officer, up from about 10% five years ago.</p><p> During the pandemic, some companies moved people into diversity leadership if they were an ethnic minority, says</p> Dani Monroe, even when they weren&#39;t qualified. Monroe served as CDO for Mass General Brigham, a Boston-based hospital system and one of the largest employers in the state, until 2021 and convenes a yearly gathering of more than 100 CDOs.<p></p><p> “These were knee-jerk reactions,” she says of the hurried CDO hires, adding that some of those elevations didn&#39;t create much impact, leaving both sides feeling disillusioned.</p><h3> On-the-job obstruction</h3><p> American workers are split on the importance of a diverse workforce, <a href="https://www.pewresearch.org/social-trends/2023/05/17/diversity-equity-and-inclusion-in-the-workplace/" target="_blank" class="icon none">surveys find</a> .</p><p> Diversity chiefs also encounter obstruction from top executives, says Melinda Starbird, a human resources and diversity executive who has worked at <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/T" class="">AT&amp;T</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span></p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/SBUX" class="company-name">Starbucks</a> and OfferUp, an online marketplace. Leaders sometimes associate diversity efforts with mandates, such as the equal-employment rules that apply to federal contractors. Those requirements for compliance can create executive resistance that bleeds over into other cultural or policy shifts, such as <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/biden-to-sign-bill-making-juneteenth-a-federal-holiday-11623944038?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">adding Juneteenth</a> as a company holiday, she says.<p></p><p> “Even if you report to the CEO, it&#39;s still a battle and it&#39;s a smaller budget,” says Starbird, who was laid off from OfferUp in November during a broader restructuring.</p><p> Many diversity executives feel a lack of buy-in from their colleagues. In <a href="https://urldefense.com/v3/__https://world50.com/impact?utm_source=wsj&amp;utm_medium=pr&amp;utm_campaign=2023idreport__;!!F0Stn7g!EGLdSj-lMiFGnMwE-GKlWcgVj1tXMu0_-ZbTIyBUUYuQV0JylSZhtrfPiJ-A4c5JWSBx3Po2kxjQHsQPCw$" target="_blank" class="icon none">a survey</a> of 138 diversity executives conducted this spring by World 50 Group, a networking organization for corporate leaders, 82% said they had sufficient influence to do their job, down 6 percentage points from 2022. Asked if they felt supported by middle managers, 41% said yes, an 8-percentage-point drop.</p><p> Since the Supreme Court overturned affirmative action in June, companies are anticipating spillover legal action could have an impact on them. Those that are still hiring CDOs want people who can help the board navigate the political and legal landscape of diversity work and figure out how to take defensive moves to shield them from litigation, says Tina Shah Paikeday, global leader of Russell Reynolds&#39;s diversity, equity and inclusion practice.</p><p> “They recognize it would be smart to get ahead of that.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820155?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> David Kenny, chief executive of Nielsen, says efforts to restructure compensation to make it more equitable created a backlash.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Nielsen</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> People are more resistant to company-backed efforts to advance diversity when they are worried about their own jobs, whether because of impending layoffs or disruptions from AI, says David Kenny, chief executive of Nielsen, the media-ratings company.</p><p> Kenny was both CEO and CDO for a time, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chief-executive-or-diversity-chief-nielsens-ceo-is-both-11608908446?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">taking on</a> the diversity role to emphasize how important it was to the future of the business. Even as CEO, it could be a tough sell. Efforts to restructure compensation to make it more equitable created a backlash.</p><p> “A lot of it is, &#39;I&#39;m losing my slice of the pie,&#39; ” he says. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/newsroom-feedback/9d40dc7b-c819-4785-ab9c-4c1e1272d3a7.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Write to Te-Ping Chen at <a href="mailto:Te-ping.Chen@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Te-ping.Chen@wsj.com</a> and Lauren Weber at <a href="mailto:Lauren.Weber@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Lauren.Weber@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/bef2e1de-18c2-41e5-86fb-8b21bfe3c1c7.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 16:06:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chief-diversity-officer-cdo-business-corporations-e110a82f</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/chief-diversity-officer-cdo-business-corporations-e110a82f<author><![CDATA[Te-Ping ChenLauren Weber]]></author><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>WSJ公司</category><category>Human Resources Consulting</category><category> Broadcasting</category><category> Cable Broadcasting</category><category> Accounting/Consulting</category><category>商业/消费者服务</category><category>Business Consultancy</category><category>媒体/娱乐</category><category>劳工/人事</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>Workplace Diversity</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Netflix</category><category> NFLX</category><category>华特迪士尼</category><category>DIS</category><category> AT&amp;T</category><category> T</category><category>华纳兄弟探索公司 A 系列</category><category>世界BD</category><category>华纳兄弟探索公司</category><category>劳动</category><category>人员</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>workplace diversity</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>human resources consulting</category><category> broadcasting</category><category> cable broadcasting</category><category> accounting</category><category> consulting</category><category> business</category><category>消费服务</category><category>business consultancy</category><category>媒体</category><category>娱乐</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[It’s Time to Bring Back Asylums]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Recent cases of violence by the mentally ill highlight the need to reconsider a long-maligned institution that now offers a promising solution. <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820388/?width=1000&amp;size=0.8" alt="A full caption appears at the end of the article." referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> A full caption appears at the end of the article. Eleanor Shakespeare <span>Eleanor Shakespeare</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001066770"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001066770"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name">David Oshinsky</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 21, 2023 10:56 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/its-time-to-bring-back-the-asylum-ec01fb2"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> The ongoing saga of the severely mentally ill in America is stirring attention again in a sadly familiar way. In Los Angeles in early 2022, a 70-year-old nurse was murdered while waiting for a bus, and two days later a young graduate student was stabbed to death in an upscale furniture store where she worked. That same week in New York City, a 40-year-old financial analyst was pushed onto the subway tracks as a train was arriving, killing her instantly.</p><p> All three assaults, random and unprovoked, were committed by unsheltered homeless men with violent pasts and long histories of mental illness. In New York, the perpetrator had warned a psychiatrist during one of his many hospitalizations of his intention to commit that very crime. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="wsj-article-pullquote article__inset__pullquote "><p class="pullquote-content article__inset__pullquote__quote"> <span class="l-qt article__inset__pullquote__mark--left">“</span> The death of Jordan Neely speaks volumes about the public&#39;s fear of the aggressive and sometimes violent behavior of the mentally ill. <span class="r-qt article__inset__pullquote__mark--right">”</span></p></div></div><p> Then came the chance encounter this May that led to the death of Jordan Neely on a Manhattan-bound subway car. Homeless and schizophrenic, Neely had spent most of his adult life in and out of emergency rooms, psychiatric wards and prison. He had 42 prior arrests, mostly for nuisance crimes, but also for assault. He&#39;d recently pleaded guilty to punching an elderly woman in the face, fracturing her eye socket.</p><p> What happened in the moments leading up to his death is still in dispute. While a jury will decide whether another passenger&#39;s chokehold on Neely was second-degree manslaughter or an act of self-defense, the attention the incident received speaks volumes about the public&#39;s fear of the aggressive and sometimes violent behavior of the mentally ill. Most of all, Neely&#39;s death highlights the failures of a mental health system that allows profoundly disturbed people to slip through the cracks.</p><p> On an average night, according to the US Department of Housing and Urban Development, close to 600,000 people in the country will be homeless—a figure seen by many as an undercount. More than 40% will be “unsheltered,” or “living in places not suitable for human habitation,” and about 20% will be dealing with severe mental illness.</p><p> Experts sharply disagree about the contribution of homelessness to rising crime rates. Some emphasize that the most of these crimes are low-level victimless offenses, such as loitering or public urination. But others note the disproportionately high level of all crimes, including assaults and homicides, committed by those battling homelessness and mental issues simultaneously.</p><p> Had Jordan Neely and the others been born a generation or two earlier, they probably would not have wound up on the streets. There was an alternative back then: state psychiatric hospitals <sub>,</sub> popularly known as asylums. Massive, architecturally imposing, and set on bucolic acreage, they housed close to 600,000 patients by the 1950s, totaling half the nation&#39;s hospital population. Today, that number is 45,000 and falling. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="wsj-article-pullquote article__inset__pullquote "><p class="pullquote-content article__inset__pullquote__quote"> <span class="l-qt article__inset__pullquote__mark--left">“</span> The very term &#39;asylum&#39; implies refuge for those in distress. <span class="r-qt article__inset__pullquote__mark--right">”</span></p></div></div><p> Asylums were created for humane ends. The very term implies refuge for those in distress. The idea was to separate the insane, who were innocently afflicted, from the criminals and prostitutes who were then commonly referred to as the “unworthy poor.” Asylums were popular because they provided treatment in isolated settings, far from temptation, while relieving families of their most burdensome members.</p><p> But “insanity” in these years cast a very wide net. A typical asylum included patients who were suffering from alcoholism, dementia, depression and epilepsy, as well as such now defunct diagnoses as “lunacy” and “melancholia.” The usual stay was marked in years, not months, as evidenced by the rows of crosses in asylum graveyards.</p><p> Over time, the number of institutionalized patients far outpaced the state&#39;s willingness to support them. Funding and oversight disappeared. And this, in turn, produced a flood of expos <em>é</em> s—some embellished, others sadly true—portraying these institutions as torture chambers where icepick lobotomies, electric shock, sterilization and solitary confinement turned humans into zombies.</p><p> A seemingly revolutionary solution soon appeared—a new drug with the potential to treat psychotic disorders such as schizophrenia and bipolar disorder. First marketed in 1955 under the brand name Thorazine, it became the psychiatric equivalent of antibiotics and the polio vaccine. Why keep patients locked away in sadistic institutions when they could be successfully medicated close to home?</p><p> The promise of Thorazine coincided with a dramatic assault upon traditional psychiatry led by radical critics such as Michel Foucault and Thomas Szasz. Asylums existed to enslave those who ignored society&#39;s norms, they believed. Who could say with assurance that the people locked away in these places were any more or less insane than the authorities who put them there? It seemed a perfect fit for the 1960s, appealing to emerging rights groups and a counterculture scornful of elites. “If you talk to God, you are praying,” Szasz declared. “If God talks to you, you are schizophrenic.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="465" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820028?width=700&amp;height=465" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> President John F. Kennedy signs the Community Mental Health Act, October 1963. The law aimed to shift treatment of the mentally ill from asylums to local clinics, but the results were likened by one critic to &#39;a psychiatric Titanic.&#39;</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Bill Allen/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> In October 1963, President John F. Kennedy put his signature to the last bill he would ever sign—the Community Mental Health Act. It aimed to demolish the walled-off world of the asylum in favor of 1,500 local clinics where patients could receive the drugs and therapies they needed. Kennedy had a personal stake in the legislation: His sister, Rosemary, had undergone an experimental lobotomy that left her severely disabled. On paper, at least, deinstitutionalization seemed both more humane and more likely to succeed. Then reality set in.</p><p> Closing the asylums was the easy part. Getting people to accept a mental health clinic next to their local church or elementary school proved a much tougher sell. Asylum inmates returned home to find their former neighbors unprepared and often unwilling to help. Most of the clinics never materialized. And the promise of Thorazine was blunted, in part, by its nasty side effects. Surveys of those released from state asylums found that close to 30% were either homeless or had “no known address” within six months of their discharge. One critic likened it to “a psychiatric Titanic.”</p><p> A few voices had predicted as much. In 1973, a Wisconsin psychiatrist named Darold Treffert wrote an essay about the dangerous direction in which his profession was headed. His colleagues had become so fixated on guarding the patient&#39;s civil liberties, he noted, that they had lost sight of the patient&#39;s illness. What worried him was the full-throated endorsement of recent laws and court decisions that severely restricted involuntary commitments. What purpose was served by giving people who couldn&#39;t take care of themselves the freedom to live as they wished? He titled his piece, “Dying With Their Rights On.”</p><p> Treffert was referring to cases like Lessard v. Schmidt (1972), where a federal court ruled that involuntary commitment must be limited to cases involving the “extreme likelihood” that someone “will do immediate harm to himself or others”—a very strict standard. Three years later, the Supreme Court tightened things further by asserting that authorities had been too cavalier in locking away the “harmless mentally ill.” In O&#39;Connor v. Donaldson, it declared: “Mere public intolerance or animosity cannot constitutionally justify the deprivation of a person&#39;s physical liberty.”</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>Should we return to the asylum model for treating the mentally ill?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Enter Joyce Brown, a 40-year-old woman who went by the street name “Billie Boggs.” The year was 1987, and Brown was living atop a heating vent on New York&#39;s tony Upper East Side. It was a tense time for the nation&#39;s largest cities, with exploding crime rates, rampant crack addiction, the AIDS crisis and thousands of homeless people camping in parks, bus stations, subway tunnels and doorways. Under extreme pressure, New York&#39;s Mayor Edward Koch authorized the involuntary commitment of those living unsheltered on the streets. Brown was the first to be confined.</p><p> Little was known about her beyond her struggles with heroin and a diagnosis of schizophrenia following her eviction from a New Jersey shelter. Brown was more of a nuisance than a threat to the neighborhood—stopping traffic, screaming at pedestrians, using the sidewalk as her toilet. Social workers who periodically visited her worried that she ate poorly, never bathed and lacked the clothing to handle New York&#39;s brutal weather. Some viewed her as self-negligent to the point of being suicidal.</p><p> Taken to Bellevue Hospital, Brown was bathed, deloused and given antipsychotic drugs. Four psychiatrists confirmed the diagnosis of chronic schizophrenia. Bellevue contained a courtroom where patients could challenge their confinement before a state-appointed judge. Most were represented by a public defender, but the American Civil Liberties Union took on Brown&#39;s case, claiming that her confinement violated federal court guidelines.</p><p> Ironically, Brown turned out to be her own best witness. Carefully medicated, she testified thoughtfully enough to convince the judge that the evidence before him was too ambiguous to merit the loss of her liberty. But he surely was conflicted, writing: “There must be some civilized alternatives other than involuntary hospitalization or the street.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="967" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820024?width=639&amp;height=967" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Joyce Brown, whose involuntary commitment to New York&#39;s Bellevue Hospital sparked a civil-rights lawsuit, speaks at Harvard Law School in 1988.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Carol Francavilla/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Unfortunately, there weren&#39;t. An appeals court reversed the decision to free Brown, leading her to refuse all medication. Another trial was held to determine whether antipsychotic drugs could be forced upon her, and this time she prevailed. The city, weary of lawsuits, chose to discharge her rather than to appeal.</p><p> Brown became an instant celebrity. She traveled the TV talk show circuit as “the most famous homeless person in America” and even gave a lecture of sorts at Harvard Law School. “I like the streets, and I am entitled to live the way I want to live,” she explained. Offered a room at a “residential hotel,” she quickly returned to the life that she knew best, panhandling for drug money at the Port Authority Bus Terminal before fading from public view. She died in 2005 at age 58.</p><p> The questions her case raised, however, are more relevant than ever. How does a civilized society deal with severely mentally ill people who refuse assistance? What constitutes the sort of behavior that requires forced hospitalization? Is it time to bring back the asylum?</p><p> These issues are intertwined with a fundamental change brought about by deinstitutionalization. Put simply, civil libertarians and disability rights advocates have largely replaced psychiatrists as the arbiters of care for the severely mentally ill. And a fair number of them, with the best of intentions, seem to view the choices of those they represent as an alternative lifestyle rather than the expression of a sickness requiring aggressive medical care. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><div class="wsj-article-pullquote article__inset__pullquote "><p class="pullquote-content article__inset__pullquote__quote"> <span class="l-qt article__inset__pullquote__mark--left">“</span> The enormous vacuum created by deinstitutionalization has been a calamity for both the mentally ill and society at large. <span class="r-qt article__inset__pullquote__mark--right">”</span></p></div></div><p> The enormous vacuum created by deinstitutionalization has been a calamity for both the mentally ill and society at large. The role once occupied by the asylum has been transferred to the institutions perhaps least able to deal with mental health issues—prisons and jails. The number of inmates in the US in 1955 was 185,000; today, that figure is 1,900,000.</p><p> Unsurprisingly, the nation&#39;s three largest mental health facilities are the Los Angeles County Jail, the Cook County Jail in Chicago, and Rikers Island in New York City. Approximately one quarter of their inmates have been diagnosed with a serious mental disorder.</p><p> In this massive system, the mentally ill are less likely to make bail, more likely to be repeat offenders and far more likely to be victimized by other inmates. Given the sheer numbers, maintaining order in these prisons and jails depends heavily on antipsychotic medication. It&#39;s hard to imagine a worse environment for the safety, much less the treatment, of the mentally ill.</p><p> Meanwhile, state mental hospitals continue to shrink. Gone is the laundry list of afflictions that marked asylum life in the 1950s. The majority of the current patients are there “involuntarily”—people who have been judged a danger to themselves or to others, who have been found not guilty of a crime by reason of insanity, or who are being evaluated for their competency to stand trial. Because so many psychiatric beds have disappeared, the waiting period for admission can take months, which means that inmates languish in jail without having been convicted of a crime.</p><p> In the past decade, a growing number of scholars from across the ideological spectrum have suggested a return to asylums. Among them is Ezekiel Emanuel, a leading medical ethicist, who joined with two colleagues in 2015 to recommend the building of “safe, modern and humane” state institutions to end the revolving door of homelessness-hospitalization-prison that passes for policy today. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-820034?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Actress Louise Fletcher as the sadistic Nurse Ratched in the 1975 film &#39;One Flew Over The Cuckoo&#39;s Nest,&#39; starring Jack Nicholson (right).</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: United Artists/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The model they suggested is the Worcester Recovery Center in Massachusetts, a facility for 320 long-term patients with private rooms and “a recovery-inspired residential design.” Opened in 2012 on the grounds of a long-abandoned state asylum, it cost $300 million to complete, making it one of the most expensive non-road construction projects in the state&#39;s history.</p><p> There is little doubt of the need for it, and the early signs, including surveys of recovery outcomes, are encouraging. Since the goal is to serve patients, rather than to warehouse them, the price can be steep. In 2015 Massachusetts spent $55,000 per prison inmate, with some additional costs for those with serious mental health issues. Meanwhile, the Worcester Recovery Center, with an annual budget of $60 million, spent close to four times that sum per patient. How this will play out in the long run, and how many other states will follow, remains to be seen.</p><p> The very word “asylum” brings shivers to those old enough to remember its abuses. It has a disturbing cultural legacy to confront in the sadistic Nurse Ratched of “One Flew Over the Cuckoo&#39;s Nest.” Bringing it back in any form will face the twin obstacles of cost and image. But for the most vulnerable among us, who exist in a world of peril to themselves and to others, it is a far better option than the alternatives of homelessness and incarceration.</p><p> <em>David Oshinsky directs the Division of Medical Humanities at NYU Langone Health. His books include “Bellevue: Three Centuries of Medicine and Mayhem at America&#39;s Most Storied Hospital” and “Polio: An American Story,” which won the 2006 Pulitzer Prize for history.</em></p><p> ***</p><p> Photo illustration caption: Clockwise from top left: A patient record from a state mental hospital in Massachusetts; Bellevue Hospital in 1962; a sign at a protest following the death of Jordan Neely, May 5; a New York subway train; a doctor examines a patient at a state mental hospital in New York, 1937; a bottle of Thorazine, the antipsychotic drug introduced in 1955; the Twin Towers jail in Los Angeles; nurses restrain a patient at an asylum in Ohio, ca. 1946.</p><p> <em>Source photographs for illustration: Max Denisov/Unsplash; Vlad Hilitanu/Unsplash; Renan Kamikoga/Unsplash; Tim Gouw/Unsplash; Diego Jimenez/Unsplash; Jerry Cooke/Getty Images; John Tlumacki/The Boston Globe/Getty Images; ROBYN BECK/AFP/Getty Images; Spencer Platt/Getty Images; Jack Harris/Associated Press; School of Pharmacy, University of Wisconsin, Madison, Wisconsin/Smithsonian Institution; Alfred Eisenstaedt/The LIFE Picture Collection/Shutterstock</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 14:56:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/its-time-to-bring-back-the-asylum-ec01fb2</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/its-time-to-bring-back-the-asylum-ec01fb2<category>建筑施工</category><category>住宅建筑施工</category><category>建造</category><category>房地产/建筑</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>Homicides</category><category> Welfare/Social Services</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>homicides</category><category> welfare</category><category> social services</category><category>建筑施工</category><category>住宅建筑施工</category><category>建造</category><category>房地产</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[How a Tiny Archipelago Gave Russia a Foothold in the Atlantic]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>长期捕鱼协议对法罗群岛的经济至关重要，但它也让俄罗斯船只能够进入北大西洋<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001072705"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="572" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821413?width=860&amp;height=572" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">法罗群岛的克里斯蒂安港。渔业是其支柱产业之一。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：法新社，盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001072705"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sune-engel-rasmussen" itemprop="url" rel="author">苏尼·恩格尔·拉斯穆森</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 7 月 21 日上午 8:46 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-a-tiny-archipelago-gave-russian-ships-a-foothold-in-the-atlantic-83e9c31d"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>尽管自俄罗斯入侵乌克兰以来，欧洲一直在努力缩小安全漏洞，但北大西洋的一个小岛群为俄罗斯船只在其水域和港口捕鱼和停靠提供了漏洞，其中包括被指控从事间谍活动和破坏活动的船只。</p><p> Western nations are growing increasingly wary of what&#39;s going on in and around the Faroe Islands, a self-governing territory under the Kingdom of Denmark which has a longstanding fishing agreement with Moscow. The agreement lets Russian vessels call at Faroese ports, circumventing a ban from European Union ports.</p><p> It also gives Russian vessels fishing rights in waters shared between the Faroes and the UK, prompting the British government to push the Faroese to suspend it—something the islands&#39; leaders haven&#39;t yet agreed to do.</p><p> The dispute illustrates how Europe has sharpened its focus on <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russian-submarines-test-nato-in-icy-north-atlantic-11593682201?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">waterways in the North Sea and the North Atlantic</a> , as it enters a new era of great-power conflict with Russia after its invasion of Ukraine.</p><p> The Faroese-UK special area falls within a strategic transit route between Greenland, Iceland and the UK, known as the GIUK Gap, which since the Cold War has been a key access point for military operations in the North Atlantic. As countries have become more dependent on offshore energy facilities and <a href="https://www.wsj.com/podcasts/wsj-the-future-of-everything/melting-ice-undersea-cables-how-the-arctic-is-getting-fast-internet/2a204ef7-e522-45cb-946c-44fc1e4600d7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">undersea fiber cables</a> that enable internet access and financial transactions, the gap&#39;s importance has grown.</p><p> “Seabed critical infrastructure and energy infrastructure have been targeted and will be targeted in the future. It is an awareness that the US and Europe have been waking up to in the last year,” said Rebecca Pincus, director of the Polar Institute at the Wilson Center in Washington, DC </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821416?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A fishing boat on the quayside in Grimsby, England. The UK and the Faroe Islands share some fishing waters.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: oli scarff/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Following criticism from the British, the Faroe Islands last week implemented new restrictions meaning that only 31 Russian vessels named in their bilateral agreement can access its ports. Previously, other Russian fishing vessels not named in the agreement could legally transship cargo or undergo repairs in Faroese harbors. Faroese Foreign Minister Høgni Hoydal said in an interview that the new step will decrease the number of Russian vessels by about 60%.</p><p> However, the named Russian ships will still be able to fish in the so-called special zone that the Faroes share with the UK, where British authorities aren&#39;t allowed to inspect them, according to a 1999 agreement with Denmark.</p><p> Mark Spencer, the British minister for food, farming and fisheries, told his Faroese counterpart Dennis Holm in January that “the decision to renew your deal with Russia impacts upon our bilateral relationship,” and expressed “grave concern that this situation may arise again during 2023,” according to a letter obtained by the Wall Street Journal through a freedom of information request.</p><p> A UK government spokesperson said London will continue to seek a ban on Russian vessels fishing in the UK-Faroes special area.</p><p> The <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/whos-killing-off-residents-of-this-island-nation-crime-writers-1524243819?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">wind-lashed Faroes</a> , with a population of 54,000 people, 70,000 sheep and around a half-a-million breeding pairs of puffins, have jurisdiction over their own trade policy and aren&#39;t a member of the EU, but their foreign and security policy is determined in Denmark. The Faroese-Russian fishing agreement, which dates back to 1977, allows the Faroese to fish primarily for cod in the Barents Sea and Russians to fish for herring and mackerel in Faroese waters. Fish constitutes about <a href="http://www.wsj.com/articles/faeroe-islands-boom-by-selling-salmon-to-russia-1424483776" target="_blank" class="icon none">90% of Faroese exports</a> . Danish politicians have said the agreement makes the Faroes, and by extension Denmark, vulnerable to Russian espionage and creates a rift with the EU. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821415?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Mark Spencer said the British government is concerned about the Faroe Islands&#39; deal with Russia.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Justin Ng/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-warned-ukraine-not-to-attack-nord-stream-7777939b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">sabotage last year of the Nord Stream pipeline</a> in the Baltic Sea showed the vulnerability of underwater infrastructure and the difficulty in identifying culprits. For instance, 77% of the UK&#39;s gas is imported from Norway through pipelines under the North Sea.</p><p> “Russia has invested a lot into being able to threaten these areas and carry out clandestine undersea activities,” said Nick Childs, senior fellow for naval forces and maritime security at the International Institute for Strategic Studies in London. “It is very much back in vogue again.”</p><p> Recent incidents have stoked anxiety in European capitals about the Russian presence in the Faroes.</p><p> Last year, after 2.6 miles of an undersea fiber-optic cable connecting a Norwegian satellite station with the mainland was cut and vanished without a trace, marine tracking data showed a Russian fishing trawler had crisscrossed over the cable more than 140 times in the days before it was severed, prompting suspicions of sabotage. The trawler&#39;s movements were first reported by Norwegian media outlets.</p><p> Following the incident, the trawler, Melkart-5, docked in the Faroes until May this year. Andrey Roman, deputy director of Murman SeaFood, which owns Melkart-5, denied allegations that the vessel had been involved in sabotage.</p><p> “Our company is a completely commercial company,” Roman said. “Our vessels are subject to control in Norwegian ports and on the high seas by the Norwegian authorities.”</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> In November last year, Norwegian police in the northern port of Kirkenes searched two Russian fishing trawlers, Lira and Ester, which had arrived there straight from the Faroes, and found Soviet-era military radio equipment behind locked doors. The chief of Norwegian intelligence in the region told national media at the time that he suspected the vessels could be involved in espionage.</p><p> The two vessels currently have their transponders turned off, but have docked in the Faroes more than 200 times since 2015, according to marine trafficking data. They are both among the 31 vessels allowed to call at Faroese ports, according to a list provided by the Faroe Islands Fisheries Inspection.</p><p> A spokesperson for the Norwegian Police Security Service declined to comment on the allegations against the three Russian vessels, but said Norway was a target for Russian intelligence services, and that “it is obviously possible that ships, including civilian ones, can be used by Russian authorities as platforms to collect information as part of their activities.”</p><p> Hoydal, the Faroese foreign minister, said Faroese authorities had not detected any malign activity from Russian vessels in their waters. He also pointed out that the islands&#39; trade with Russia doesn&#39;t violate EU <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-shadow-of-sanctions-russia-courts-friends-boasts-resilience-at-flagship-economic-forum-d299b6bc?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">sanctions against Moscow</a> , which exclude food items—although no EU nations currently trade fish with Russia.</p><p> “Since the beginning of Russia&#39;s war in Ukraine, we have introduced the same sanctions as the EU,” Hoydal said. “But we honor our agreements.”</p><p> A Faroese lawmaker in Copenhagen, Sjurdur Skaale, said the EU should remove tariffs on Faroese exports of processed seafood products to help the islands reduce their trade with Russia and suspend the agreement.</p><p> The Faroese earned privileged access to the Russian market in 2014, following the invasion of Crimea, when the islands chose not to follow EU sanctions on Russia. However, Iceland—another small territory depending on the seafood business—followed the EU&#39;s lead and was targeted by Russian counter sanctions. The following year, Iceland&#39;s economy contracted by about 1%.</p><p> “The stakes are high for smaller countries and territories,” Pincus said.</p><p> Write to Sune Engel Rasmussen at <a href="mailto:sune.rasmussen@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">sune.rasmussen@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 12:46:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-a-tiny-archipelago-gave-russian-ships-a-foothold-in-the-atlantic-83e9c31d</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-a-tiny-archipelago-gave-russian-ships-a-foothold-in-the-atlantic-83e9c31d<author><![CDATA[Sune Engel Rasmussen]]></author><category>乌克兰</category><category>Agriculture</category><category> Fishing</category><category> Port/Harbor Operations</category><category> Water Transport/Shipping</category><category>运输/物流</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>Trade/External Payments</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>国际关系</category><category>International Sanctions</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>Espionage</category><category> Trade Barriers/Restrictions</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>Ukraine</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>trade</category><category> external payments</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>国际关系</category><category>international sanctions</category><category>政治</category><category>espionage</category><category> trade barriers</category><category> restrictions</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>agriculture</category><category> fishing</category><category> port</category><category> harbor operations</category><category> water transport</category><category> shipping</category><category>运输</category><category>后勤</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Beijing Rushes to Shore Up Battered Private Economy. Skepticism Abounds.]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> China vows to promote a private sector wobbly from years of regulatory crackdowns and pandemic controls, but investors aren&#39;t convinced <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001072909"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821472?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A job fair in Chongqing. China&#39;s efforts to rekindle the private sector risks exacerbating youth unemployment</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Agence France-Presse/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001072909"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/stella-yifan-xie" itemprop="url" rel="author">Stella Yifan Xie</a></span> in Hong Kong and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/raffaele-huang" itemprop="url" rel="author">Raffaele Huang</a></span> in Singapore</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> July 21, 2023 8:32 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/beijing-rushes-to-shore-up-battered-private-economy-skepticism-abounds-80c1a23c"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> China&#39;s leadership is lavishing the country&#39;s beleaguered private sector with a sweeping show of support as <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-economy-barely-grows-as-recovery-fades-5652a92a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a nascent economic recovery falters</a> .</p><p> But grand declarations and rhetoric alone won&#39;t suffice, say economists and investors. Sluggish domestic demand and a widely held view that Beijing still favors its state-owned enterprises mean that sentiment among the private business owners—a group that <a href="https://www.wsj.com/livecoverage/china-xi-jinping-communist-party-congress/card/in-china-the-state-sector-is-in-private-sector-stutters-jyOYiDqUFiSBISBHVyyS?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">accounts for most of the economy&#39;s dynamism</a> and hiring—isn&#39;t likely to turn around, at least not in the near term.</p><p> In a high-profile pronouncement this week, China&#39;s Communist Party and the country&#39;s cabinet jointly unveiled a list of more than 30 guidelines vowing to make the private sector “bigger, better and stronger.” Authorities said the measures would level the playing field between privately-run and state-owned enterprises, promising to break down market barriers, expand financing for privately held companies and engage them in future policy consultations.</p><p> Beijing&#39;s outreach to the private sector—a segment that contributes about 60% of China&#39;s total output and 80% of urban employment—comes as growth in the world&#39;s second-largest economy is decelerating on multiple fronts. It also marks a reprieve from the previous three years, in which Chinese officials decimated industries including after-school education and property with a series of regulatory crackdowns and strict limits. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821477?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A truck production line in Xian. China&#39;s leadership has rolled out incentives to boost vehicle sales.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: FLORENCE LO/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The measures, unveiled on Wednesday, drew public praise from several prominent entrepreneurs such as <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TCEHY" class="company-name">Tencent Holdings</a> &#39; low-profile co-founder Pony Ma. The videogame and social media titan and other major internet companies have seen their business and profits pummeled by Beijing&#39;s sudden changes in regulation in the last two years.</p><p> Over the past few weeks, Chinese officials have showered investors and the business community with attention and public promises to buttress the sector. China&#39;s Premier Li Qiang met with executives from the country&#39;s biggest tech companies including <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/BABA" class="company-name">Alibaba Group Holding</a> and TikTok parent ByteDance, encouraging them to support the economy through innovation.</p><p> Officials also met local business leaders in the manufacturing and consumption sectors to survey the difficulties they face, and held meetings to reassure business associations from the US, Europe and Japan that the country remains open for foreign investment. They also rolled out incentives to boost vehicle sales.</p><p> Such support comes after China&#39;s internet companies lost over $1 trillion in market value since late 2020, when authorities scrapped fintech giant Ant Group&#39;s blockbuster initial public offering, kicking off a series of regulatory crackdowns. Government raids on global consultancies including Bain &amp; Co. this year, as well as an expanded version of anti-espionage law have also dampened animal spirits in the business community.</p><p> Despite this, economists and private entrepreneurs interviewed by The Wall Street Journal say that three years of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-covid-dropped-restrictions-reopen-xi-11673534796?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">strict control of Covid-19</a> and concurrent regulatory campaigns have taken its toll. The recent purges in China&#39;s internet and private tutoring industry have left entrepreneurs wary of unexpectedly falling afoul of the Communist Party&#39;s social goals, said George Magnus, research associate at Oxford University and former chief economist at <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/UBS" class="">UBS</a> <span class="company-name-type">.</span></p><p></p><p> “The overall attitude toward the private sector is still one where they are subordinate to the interest of the state,” he said.</p><p> Much of the caution among private business and investors also reflects long-term economic headwinds such as the country&#39;s shrinking population as well as elevated local government and household debt. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-821478?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A construction site in Zhejiang province. Ongoing pains in China&#39;s housing market could worsen investor sentiment.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: hector retamal/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The private-sector&#39;s share of China&#39;s 100 largest listed companies by market value dropped from a peak of 55% in mid 2021 to 39% this June, close to its lowest levels in more than three years, according to a forthcoming research report by the Washington, DC-based think tank Peterson Institute for International Economics, or PIIE.</p><p> Private sector investment shrank by 0.2% in the first half of 2023 from a year earlier, the first contraction since official data collection began in 2005, with the exception of 2020, when the economy was racked by the pandemic. In contrast, investment by state-controlled firms expanded 8.1% in the same period.</p><p> Profits at private sector firms, more exposed to falling exports and weak consumer spending, reported a 21% plunge in the first five months of the year. Profits at state-owned enterprises fell 17.7%.</p><p> Ongoing pains in China&#39;s housing market could worsen investor sentiment. Investment by real-estate developers likely accounts for roughly one-third of private investment, according to Tianlei Huang, a research fellow at PIIE.</p><p> The stakes are high for Beijing to rekindle business confidence. A failure to resuscitate the ailing private sector risks pushing Beijing&#39;s full-year growth target of around 5% further out of reach. It may also exacerbate already high youth unemployment.</p><p> For years, private firms, in particular those in the technology, education and property sectors, have absorbed a large share of China&#39;s college graduates.</p><p> Analysts say years of regulatory tightening in those sectors and ongoing distress in the real-estate market have dried up career opportunities for young professionals, helping push China&#39;s youth jobless rate to a record of 21.3% in June.</p><p> In the longer run, the private sector&#39;s retreat would reduce overall efficiency and lead to slower productivity growth, consequences that could ultimately suppress China&#39;s growth potential, economists say.</p><p> Zhang Xuan, a Beijing-based partner of a private-equity firm focusing on technology investment said Beijing&#39;s most recent pledge on supporting the private sector sent a positive message to investors, but hasn&#39;t reassured him about containing a broader economic downturn.</p><p> “The long-term performance of the market can&#39;t simply be governed by a couple policy documents,” he said.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Xiao Xiao in Beijing contributed to this article.</p><p> Write to Stella Yifan Xie at <a href="mailto:stella.xie@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">stella.xie@wsj.com</a> and Raffaele Huang at <a href="mailto:raffaele.huang@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">raffaele.huang@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Fri, 21 Jul 2023 12:32:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/beijing-rushes-to-shore-up-battered-private-economy-skepticism-abounds-80c1a23c</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/beijing-rushes-to-shore-up-battered-private-economy-skepticism-abounds-80c1a23c<author><![CDATA[Stella Yifan XieRaffaele Huang]]></author><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>经济表现/指标</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> ByteDance</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>经济表现</category><category>指标</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category></item></channel></rss>